Logit Knowledge Distillation has gained substantial
research interest in recent years due to its simplicity and
lack of requirement for intermediate feature alignment;
however, it suffers from limited interpretability in its
decision-making process. To address this, we propose
implicit Clustering Distillation (iCD): a simple and
effective method that mines and transfers interpretable
structural knowledge from logits, without requiring
ground-truth labels or feature-space alignment. iCD
leverages Gram matrices over decoupled local logit
representations to enable student models to learn latent
semantic structural patterns. Extensive experiments on
benchmark datasets demonstrate the effectiveness of iCD
across diverse teacher-student architectures, with
particularly strong performance in fine-grained
classification tasks---achieving a peak improvement of
+5.08% over the baseline.